title: clean up use_openmp in build.sh
Revert "Remove openmp flag (#1140)"
body:
This reverts commit a7137a0f9d1795fa86a25a726a3c638d17085b93.

For these code are using openmp, we have 3 choices here:

1. run them sequentially
2. run them with openmp
3. run them within the thread pool in session state

The third one is the way we want to go, but we haven't reached there.

While reverting this change, at the same time, we'll start to replace the openmp code in our cpu provider, to calls to the thread pool in SessionState. Once the work is done and there is no observable perf downgrade on major models, we'll redo the "remove openmp" change.

title: Fix error message for legacy opset (6 and lower) models at model load time
body:
Takeaway from #1138  (and another issue I closed a while ago)

An opset 6 or lower model always fails with misleading error message "Couldn't find an implementation..." which is actually misleading as it cannot find an implementation by design as the kernels are unsupported (ORT only guarantees support for opset 7 or above). So this change tries to catch such stuff at model load time and improve the out-of-the-box experience.

P.S. Opset 6 model is allowed at the gate currently because there are quite a few opset 6 models being tested and it is going to be a big work item to see if they can be converted to opset 7 or above. So such models are allowed to proceed further (with a warning logged)

title: Fix CUDA thread_local to allow multiple CUDA execution providers
body:
This fixes #1034: Can't Create Model Sessions on Different GPU
The root cause of the bug is that CUDA execution provider uses thread_local to save per-thread-context and allocator, and when two CUDA execution providers are running on the same thread there's a conflict. The fix is to add a std::unordered_map to differentiate EPs in the same thread.

For those who write convert models to onnx and test them using the runtime, debugging issues in the runtime is very painful. This request is to add features to the runtime whereby one could ask for verbose prints (with different levels) while the model is being executed.

Current runtime version is 0.5.0 and it does not have such feature.

I'd like to have options to run a model and print details about each operation.
I need a multi-level debug print option. 
Level 0: current print out
Level 1: input and output shapes after each operation
Level 2: print out -- the numpy style -- all outputs of each operation or as specified (see below)

If I specify any level 1 or 2 I would want the runtime to stop all optimizations and leave the graph alone to be as supplied.

For Level 2, a separate option could accept Operator names and patterns. If this option is specified along with Level 2 then only the matching operators will have their outputs printed out.

The alternatives are very painful and include running multiple versions of a graph, and modifying the runtime code to print out data.

title: perftest: set parallel executor and thread pool size separately

labels.name: type:enhancement
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: status:contributions-welcome
labels.description: contributions welcome; lower priority items for the core teams on this project

body: In perftest, currently, there's only `-x <pool_size>` which activates both parallel execution plan and sets the session thread pool size. It would be good for benchmarking to be able to set these things separately. I suggest changing `-x <pool_size>` to only set the pool size (and mentioning that the default is the hw thread count) and add another flag `-P` (or whatever you like) that only enables parallel execution planning, with default being sequential execution plan.
